<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="20" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="19.[123,652,240,615]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
REMARKS: The local population of spectacled bears was studied by 
<bibRefCitation author="Suarez, L." box="[471,646,328,351]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" pagination="133 - 136" refId="ref24892" refString="Suarez, L. 1988. Seasonal distribution and food habits of spectacled bears Tremarctos ornatus in the highlands of Ecuador. Studies on Neotropical Fauna and Environment 23: 133 - 136." type="journal article" year="1988">Su√°rez (1988)</bibRefCitation>
, who described their seasonal distribution and diet on the eastern slopes of Cerro Antisana. No locally collected specimens, however, are apparently preserved in museums. Although I did not see any bears in the course of my fieldwork, signs of their foraging (consisting of shredded terrestrial bromeliads whose pith is an important item of diet) were sometimes observed above treeline.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
